Title: Replace Steam Canister and Clean Drain Valve
Description:
TO REPLACE THE CANISTER
1. Turn humidifier off
2. Unit will go through drain cycle – 4 mins – and turn off when
complete
3. Disconnect main electrical power to humidifier at the circuit breaker
4. Allow the unit to cool
5. Remove front door
6. Remove electrode wires, high water probe wire, steam hose and
canister
7. Remove O-ring from groove in drain assembly using a small screw
driver
8. Insect drain assembly and remove any debris – see TO CLEAN THE
DRAIN VALVE
9. Insert new O-ring into groove in drain assembly (O-ring is provided
with Model 80 and Model 80LC canisters ) Dampen O-ring with
water before inserting canister Do not use oil, grease, or any
lubricant besides water
10. Make sure strainer is inserted into bottom of new canister
11. Insert canister into drain assembly Position canister with label facing
outward
12. Reconnect steam hose and wires ensuring wires are fully seated
13. Replace front door
14. Restore electrical power to humidifier
15. Turn humidifier On and verify green On/Off light is illuminated
16. See Start-up procedure
17. Check for leaks.




TO CLEAN THE DRAIN VALVE
1. Turn humidifier off
2. Unit will go through drain cycle – 4 mins – and turn off when
complete
3. Disconnect main electrical power to humidifier at the circuit
breaker
4. Allow the unit to cool
5. Remove front door
6. Remove electrode wires, high water probe wire, steam hose and
canister
7. With your finger swirl the fluid/precipitate mixture in the bottom of
the drain valve reservoir
8. Using a sponge or paper towels soak up the water in the reservoir,
if necessary use a wet/dry vacuum to remove residue
9. Clean the inside of the drain port (where coil projects out) by
gently swabbing with a bent cotton swab or other soft implement
10. Rinse the drain valve reservoir with clean water and vacuum as
necessary
11. Replace canister, reconnect steam hose and wires ensuring wires
are fully seated
12. Replace front door
13. Restore electrical power to humidifier
14. Turn humidifier On and verify green On/Off light is illuminated
15. See Start-up procedure
16. Check for leaks

Title: Inspect Batteries and Refill
Description:
I. Safety Precautions

    Personal Protective Equipment (PPE):

        Wear safety goggles, gloves, and protective clothing.

        Use a face shield if necessary.

    Work Area Safety:

        Ensure the forklift is turned off and the key is removed.

        Work in a well-ventilated area to avoid inhaling fumes.

        Keep sparks, flames, and smoking materials away from the battery area.

    Battery Safety:

        Be cautious of acid spills and leaks.

        Avoid short-circuiting the battery terminals.

II. Tools and Materials Needed

    Distilled water (never use tap water)

    Hydrometer (optional, for checking electrolyte levels)

    Funnel (preferably with a narrow spout)

    Clean cloth or paper towels

    Baking soda (for cleaning up acid spills)

    Wrench or pliers (if battery caps are tight)

III. Steps to Check and Refill Distilled Water

    Access the Battery Compartment:

        Locate the battery compartment on the forklift.

        Open the battery compartment cover or door as per the forklift’s design.

    Inspect the Battery:

        Check for any visible damage, leaks, or corrosion on the battery casing.

        If corrosion is present, clean the terminals with a mixture of baking soda and water, then rinse with clean water and dry.

    Open the Battery Cell Caps:

        Carefully remove the caps from the battery cells. Some batteries may have a single cover with multiple caps, while others may have individual caps.

        Use a wrench or pliers if the caps are tight, but be gentle to avoid damaging them.

    Check the Electrolyte Levels:

        Look inside each cell to check the level of the electrolyte (the liquid covering the battery plates).

        The electrolyte should cover the plates by about 1/4 to 1/2 inch (6-12 mm). If the plates are exposed, the battery needs water.

    Refill with Distilled Water:

        Using a funnel, slowly add distilled water to each cell until the electrolyte level is just above the plates.

        Do not overfill, as the electrolyte can expand during charging and overflow.

        If you accidentally overfill, use a clean syringe or turkey baster to remove excess water.

    Close the Battery Cell Caps:

        Securely replace the caps on each cell, ensuring they are tight but not over-tightened.

        Wipe away any spilled water or electrolyte with a clean cloth.

    Clean the Battery and Compartment:

        Wipe down the battery casing and surrounding area to remove any dirt or residue.

        Ensure the battery compartment is clean and dry before closing it.

    Close the Battery Compartment:

        Securely close the battery compartment cover or door.

IV. Post-Refill Checks

    Inspect for Leaks:

        After refilling, check for any leaks around the battery caps or casing.

    Charge the Battery:

        If the battery was low on water, it may need to be charged. Follow the forklift’s manual for proper charging procedures.

    Monitor Battery Performance:

        Keep an eye on the battery’s performance and water levels over the next few days to ensure everything is functioning correctly.

V. Maintenance Tips

    Regular Checks: Check the water levels in the battery regularly, especially if the forklift is used frequently.

    Avoid Overcharging: Overcharging can cause the battery to lose water more quickly. Ensure the charging system is functioning correctly.

    Keep Records: Maintain a log of when you check and refill the battery to track its maintenance history.

VI. Troubleshooting

    Low Electrolyte Levels: If the battery consistently requires frequent refilling, it may indicate overcharging or a faulty battery.

    Corrosion: If corrosion is a recurring issue, consider applying a corrosion-resistant spray or gel to the terminals.

    Battery Not Holding Charge: If the battery is not holding a charge despite proper maintenance, it may need to be replaced.

Title: Monthly Fire Extinguisher Inspection
Description:
Compliant with OSHA Standards (29 CFR 1910.157)
Purpose

To ensure all fire extinguishers are properly maintained, accessible, and in good working condition per OSHA regulations.
Scope

Applies to all portable fire extinguishers in the facility.
Responsibilities

    Facilities Manager: Oversees the program and ensures compliance.

    Designated Inspector: Trained personnel conducting monthly checks.

    Maintenance Team: Addresses issues identified during inspections.

Procedure
1. Visual Inspection

a. Location & Accessibility

    Confirm extinguisher is in its designated location.

    Ensure nothing obstructs access (min. 36” clearance per OSHA).

    Verify visibility of signage or markings.

b. Physical Condition

    Check for obvious damage (dents, corrosion, leaks, clogged nozzles).

    Inspect hose/tube for cracks or detachment.

    Verify the locking pin is intact and tamper seal unbroken.

c. Pressure & Gauge

    For gauge-type extinguishers:

        Needle must be in the "green" zone (proper pressure).

    For cartridge-operated units:

        Verify the cartridge is securely seated and undamaged.

d. Labeling & Tags

    Ensure legible operating instructions and NFPA rating label.

    Verify monthly inspection tag is present and up-to-date.

2. Documentation

    Record inspection results on the Fire Extinguisher Inspection Tag (date, initials, condition).

    Log findings in the Fire Safety Inspection Checklist.

3. Corrective Actions

    Minor Issues (e.g., obstructed access): Correct immediately.

    Major Issues (e.g., damage/low pressure): Tag as "DEFECTIVE," remove from service, and notify maintenance for repair/replacement.

4. Reporting

    Submit inspection reports to the Facilities Manager.

    Schedule annual professional maintenance (per NFPA 10).

Title: Monthly Emergency Light Inspection
Description:
To ensure emergency lighting systems are operational, properly maintained, and meet regulatory requirements for safe egress during power failures.
Scope

Applies to all battery-powered emergency lights and exit signs in the facility.
Responsibilities

    Facilities Manager: Oversees compliance and maintenance.

    Designated Inspector: Conducts monthly inspections.

    Maintenance Team: Repairs or replaces faulty units.

Procedure
1. Visual Inspection

a. Physical Condition

    Check for visible damage (cracks, corrosion, loose wiring, or missing covers).

    Ensure lenses are clean and free of obstructions.

    Verify that units are securely mounted.

b. Power Indicator

    Confirm the "power on" LED (if present) is illuminated (indicates AC power is supplied).

2. Functional Test

Manual Activation (30-Second Test)

    Simulate Power Failure:

        For units with a test button: Press and hold for 10 seconds.

        For hardwired units: Switch off the circuit breaker or unplug the unit.

    Verify Illumination:

        Emergency lights must activate immediately and remain lit for at least 30 seconds.

        Exit signs must stay illuminated (if battery-backed).

    Restore Power:

        Reactivate the circuit breaker/release the test button.

        Confirm the unit returns to charging mode (charging indicator LED on, if equipped).


3. Documentation

    Record results on the Emergency Light Inspection Tag (date, inspector initials, pass/fail).

    Update the Emergency Light Inspection Log (include unit location, test results, and actions taken).

4. Corrective Actions

    Failed Test/Defects: Tag the unit, report to maintenance, and replace batteries or bulbs within 24 hours.

    Chronic Issues: Schedule a full system inspection by a licensed electrician.

5. Annual Requirements

    Conduct a 90-minute full discharge test (per NFPA 101) to confirm battery capacity.

Title: Monthly Fire Extinguisher Inspection
Description:
Compliant with OSHA Standards (29 CFR 1910.157)
Purpose

To ensure all fire extinguishers are properly maintained, accessible, and in good working condition per OSHA regulations.
Scope

Applies to all portable fire extinguishers in the facility.
Responsibilities

    Facilities Manager: Oversees the program and ensures compliance.

    Designated Inspector: Trained personnel conducting monthly checks.

    Maintenance Team: Addresses issues identified during inspections.

Procedure
1. Visual Inspection

a. Location & Accessibility

    Confirm extinguisher is in its designated location.

    Ensure nothing obstructs access (min. 36” clearance per OSHA).

    Verify visibility of signage or markings.

b. Physical Condition

    Check for obvious damage (dents, corrosion, leaks, clogged nozzles).

    Inspect hose/tube for cracks or detachment.

    Verify the locking pin is intact and tamper seal unbroken.

c. Pressure & Gauge

    For gauge-type extinguishers:

        Needle must be in the "green" zone (proper pressure).

    For cartridge-operated units:

        Verify the cartridge is securely seated and undamaged.

d. Labeling & Tags

    Ensure legible operating instructions and NFPA rating label.

    Verify monthly inspection tag is present and up-to-date.

2. Documentation

    Record inspection results on the Fire Extinguisher Inspection Tag (date, initials, condition).

    Log findings in the Fire Safety Inspection Checklist.

3. Corrective Actions

    Minor Issues (e.g., obstructed access): Correct immediately.

    Major Issues (e.g., damage/low pressure): Tag as "DEFECTIVE," remove from service, and notify maintenance for repair/replacement.

4. Reporting

    Submit inspection reports to the Facilities Manager.

    Schedule annual professional maintenance (per NFPA 10).

Title: Monthly Emergency Light Inspection
Description:
To ensure emergency lighting systems are operational, properly maintained, and meet regulatory requirements for safe egress during power failures.
Scope

Applies to all battery-powered emergency lights and exit signs in the facility.
Responsibilities

    Facilities Manager: Oversees compliance and maintenance.

    Designated Inspector: Conducts monthly inspections.

    Maintenance Team: Repairs or replaces faulty units.

Procedure
1. Visual Inspection

a. Physical Condition

    Check for visible damage (cracks, corrosion, loose wiring, or missing covers).

    Ensure lenses are clean and free of obstructions.

    Verify that units are securely mounted.

b. Power Indicator

    Confirm the "power on" LED (if present) is illuminated (indicates AC power is supplied).

2. Functional Test

Manual Activation (30-Second Test)

    Simulate Power Failure:

        For units with a test button: Press and hold for 10 seconds.

        For hardwired units: Switch off the circuit breaker or unplug the unit.

    Verify Illumination:

        Emergency lights must activate immediately and remain lit for at least 30 seconds.

        Exit signs must stay illuminated (if battery-backed).

    Restore Power:

        Reactivate the circuit breaker/release the test button.

        Confirm the unit returns to charging mode (charging indicator LED on, if equipped).


3. Documentation

    Record results on the Emergency Light Inspection Tag (date, inspector initials, pass/fail).

    Update the Emergency Light Inspection Log (include unit location, test results, and actions taken).

4. Corrective Actions

    Failed Test/Defects: Tag the unit, report to maintenance, and replace batteries or bulbs within 24 hours.

    Chronic Issues: Schedule a full system inspection by a licensed electrician.

5. Annual Requirements

    Conduct a 90-minute full discharge test (per NFPA 101) to confirm battery capacity.
